> You've likely come across figs baked into desserts, dried and nestled onto cheese platters, or preserved and slathered on toast for breakfast. But today, we're mixing things up by pairing fig jam with tangy balsamic vinegar. The result? A sweet and savory sauce that'll transform the tender pork tenderloin it's drizzled on top of.

Adjust rack to middle position and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and finely chop @shallot{2}. Strip and finely chop enough @rosemary{¼%ounce}(strip and finely chop leaves) leaves from stems to give you 1 TBSP. Cut @Yukon Gold potatoes{24%ounce} into ½-inch cubes.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with 1 TBSP @olive oil{1%tbsp}, 2 tsp chopped rosemary, and a big pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Roast in oven until crisped, about ~{25%minutes} total (we'll add more to the sheet after 10 minutes).

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large pan over medium heat. Season @pork tenderloin{24%ounce} all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Add to pan and sear, turning occasionally, until browned all over, ~{4-6%minutes}. After potatoes have roasted 10 minutes, give them a toss, then add pork to same baking sheet. Continue roasting until pork reaches desired doneness, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Heat a large drizzle of olive oil in pan used for pork over medium heat. Add shallots and remaining chopped rosemary. Cook, tossing, until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add @fig jam{2%tbsp}, @chicken stock concentrate{2}, ½ cup @water{½%cup}, and @balsamic vinegar{10%tsp}. Stir to combine. Let simmer until thick and saucy, ~{2-4%minutes}. Remove pan from heat and add @butter{2%tbsp}, stirring to melt. Season with salt and pepper.

Let pork rest a few minutes after removing from oven, then slice into rounds. Meanwhile, place @green beans{12%ounce} in a medium #microwave-safe bowl{} with a splash of water. Cover #bowl{} with #plastic wrap{} and poke a few holes in wrap. Microwave on high until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}. Drain, then return to bowl. Add @butter{1%tbsp} and toss to melt and coat green beans.

Divide potatoes, green beans, and pork between plates. Drizzle sauce over pork and serve.